column5: {45174: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "45174",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1565",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Manipulation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may insert, delete, or manipulate data in order to influence external outcomes or hide activity, thus threatening the integrity of the data\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to delete a file from the Mozilla Firefox download directory, which could be an attempt by an adversary to manipulate data and hide their activity on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "45174", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the adversary is attempting to leverage the user\\\'s web browser (Firefox) to execute malicious code or actions, which aligns with the User Execution technique where an adversary relies on user actions to gain execution."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {29456: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n      "sid": "29456",\\n      "Technique ID": "T1595",\\n      "Technique name": "Active Scanning",\\n      "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may execute active reconnaissance scans to gather information that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n      "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect unusual ICMP ping patterns, which could indicate active scanning or reconnaissance activities by an adversary. The rule looks for specific patterns in the ICMP payload data, such as strings related to network monitoring tools like Cacti and SolarWinds, which are often used for reconnaissance purposes. column5: {44474: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44474",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects malware (GHBkdr) that uses TLS encryption to conceal its command and control traffic, which aligns with the Encrypted Channel technique where adversaries use encryption algorithms to obfuscate their network communications."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44474",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically looks for traffic over port 443, which is commonly used for HTTPS (an application layer protocol). column5: {22061: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to load a malicious IFRAME, which is a technique used by the Alureon malware to leverage web services for malicious purposes, such as relaying data or executing code on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific patterns in the IFRAME code that are indicative of the Alureon malware, which may be attempting to masquerade as a legitimate web service or content to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {300306: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "300306",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability in OpenSSL\\\'s X.509 certificate parsing code, which could allow an adversary to execute arbitrary code on the server. The rule looks for specific patterns in the SSL traffic that indicate the presence of a crafted email address field, which is a known technique used to trigger the vulnerability. By obfuscating the malicious payload within the SSL traffic, an adversary can attempt to evade detection by security tools."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "300306",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically designed to detect an attempt to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability in OpenSSL\\\'s X.509 certificate parsing code. column5: {56599: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56599",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an outbound connection attempt from the internal network to an external server, which could be an attempt to stage capabilities or download additional malware components."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56599", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol, potentially used by the malware to blend in with normal web traffic and avoid detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48502: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48502",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1529",\\n    "Technique name": "System Shutdown/Reboot",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may shutdown/reboot systems to interrupt access to, or aid in the destruction of, those systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malware variant that attempts to download and execute a command to shut down or reboot the system, which aligns with the T1529 technique of shutting down or rebooting systems to disrupt access or aid in data destruction."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48502", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1485",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Destruction",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule suggests that the detected malware variant is capable of executing commands to delete or destroy data, which corresponds to the T1485 technique of data destruction to disrupt system and network resources."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42836: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42836",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects the presence of a web shell named \\\'Chopper\\\', which is a type of malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and control over the compromised system. column5: {48818: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48818",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound connections from a compromised system to an external network, potentially indicating the use of a proxy or intermediary for command and control communication. column5: {41920: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41920",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a brute force attempt against the McAfee Virus Scan Linux authentication system, where an attacker is trying multiple combinations of authentication tokens (nailsSessionId) to gain unauthorized access."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {33939: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33939",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect malware delivered as an executable control panel (.cpl) file attachment, which requires user interaction (opening the attachment) to execute the malicious payload."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33939", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1091",\\n    "Technique name": "Replication Through Removable Media",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may move onto systems, possibly those on disconnected or air-gapped networks, by copying malware to removable media and taking advantage of Autorun features when the media is inserted into a system and executes\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "While not explicitly stated, the detection of a malicious .cpl file attachment could potentially be used to deliver malware to air-gapped systems by tricking users into executing the file from removable media."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {34709: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1499",\\n    "Technique name": "Endpoint Denial of Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may perform Endpoint Denial of Service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of services to users"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to perform a denial of service attack against the MIT Kerberos 5 service, which is a type of Endpoint Denial of Service attack aimed at disrupting the availability of the Kerberos authentication service on the targeted system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1498",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Denial of Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may perform Network Denial of Service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of targeted resources to users"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule specifically targets an Endpoint Denial of Service attack, the attack could potentially be part of a larger Network Denial of Service campaign, where the adversary attempts to degrade the availability of network resources and services."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {655: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "655",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an exploit attempt targeting the Sendmail service running on SMTP servers. column5: {48573: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48573",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to delete arbitrary files on a WordPress site by exploiting a vulnerability in the \\\'wc.status\\\' page. This involves traversing the directory structure using \\\'../\\\' to access files outside the intended directory, which aligns with the File and Directory Discovery technique where adversaries enumerate files and directories to find sensitive information or exploit vulnerabilities."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48573", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for an exploit attempt against a public-facing WordPress application, which is a common vector for initial access and aligns with the Exploit Public-Facing Application technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1882: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1882",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1033",\\n    "Technique name": "System Owner/User Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to identify the primary user, currently logged in user, set of users that commonly uses a system, or whether a user is actively using the system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule appears to be detecting an attempt to retrieve user and group ID information, which could be used by an adversary to identify the currently logged-in user or a set of users on the system. column5: {19171: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19171",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer 8 by loading the ieshims.dll library, which could allow an adversary to execute code on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19171", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic from the internal network to an external web server, suggesting an attempt to exploit a public-facing application (in this case, Internet Explorer) to gain initial access or execute code on the client system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48792: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34843",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting a malicious User-Agent string \\\'EMERY\\\' associated with the Win.Trojan.W97M malware, which is an attempt by the adversary to masquerade the malware traffic as legitimate HTTP traffic by using a custom User-Agent string."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34843", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for malicious traffic over the HTTP protocol, which is an application layer protocol. column5: {40450: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "40450",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download a file from an external source (/fr/mso/onedrive), which could be related to transferring malicious tools or files into the compromised environment, aligning with the \\\'Ingress Tool Transfer\\\' technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "40450",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects activity related to a malware downloader agent, which could potentially use a legitimate web service (in this case, OneDrive) to relay data or receive commands from an external source, corresponding to the \\\'Web Service\\\' technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42886: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42886",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound HTTP communication attempts from a potentially compromised system, where the user-agent string \\\'HttpBrowser/1.0\\\' is used, which could be an indicator of malware command and control traffic attempting to blend in with legitimate HTTP traffic by using an application layer protocol."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42886", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The use of the \\\'HttpBrowser/1.0\\\' user-agent string in the Snort rule could be an attempt by the malware to masquerade as legitimate HTTP traffic and evade detection by security tools."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {520: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "520",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to access the root directory of a TFTP server, which could be an indication of an adversary trying to transfer tools or malicious files into the network using the TFTP protocol."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "520", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1570",\\n    "Technique name": "Lateral Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files between systems in a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule specifically looks for access to the TFTP root directory from an external source, it could also be used to detect lateral movement of tools within the network using TFTP."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42395: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42395",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound connections from a Windows system infected with the Oddjob Trojan, which uses the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS) to communicate with its command and control server. column5: {1280: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1280",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects attempts to list services running on the portmapper service (port 111), which is used to discover network services on Unix-based systems. This aligns with the Network Service Discovery technique, where adversaries try to enumerate available services for potential exploitation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1280", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "By detecting attempts to list services on the portmapper, this rule may be indicative of an adversary trying to identify potential remote services to exploit for gaining initial access or lateral movement within the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19037: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19037",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1571",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Standard Port",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using a protocol and port pairing that are typically not associated\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound connections to non-standard ports 6666 and 6667, which are commonly used by IRC botnets and malware for command and control communication, indicating the use of a non-standard port pairing."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19037",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a variant of the Win.Trojan.IRCBrute malware, which is known to use IRC servers as proxies or intermediaries for command and control communication, avoiding direct connections to the attacker\\\'s infrastructure."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57879: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57879",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects the use of the \\\'Server.CreateObject\\\' and \\\'KComWExec.execCmd\\\' commands, which are associated with the Revil Kaseya ransomware. column5: {50096: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50096",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1556",\\n    "Technique name": "Modify Authentication Process",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may modify authentication mechanisms and processes to access user credentials or enable otherwise unwarranted access to accounts\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download the Responder toolkit, which is a tool used for modifying the authentication process by poisoning the LLMNR/NBT-NS/mDNS protocols and capturing credentials from Windows systems. column5: {58615: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule appears to be detecting an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the Microsoft Windows Content-Disposition header handling, which could allow remote code execution. column5: {57756: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57756",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1568",\\n    "Technique name": "Dynamic Resolution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may dynamically establish connections to command and control infrastructure to evade common detections and remediations\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect DNS Fast Flux attempts, which is a technique used by malware to dynamically resolve and connect to different command and control servers to evade detection and remediation efforts. This aligns with the \\\'Dynamic Resolution\\\' technique described in MITRE ATT&CK."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57756",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically looking for malicious activity over the DNS protocol, which is an application layer protocol. column5: {41712: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41712",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Houdini) attempting to download a malicious file (ChromeSetup.bat) using the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS), which is commonly abused by adversaries to execute code and perform tasks in the background."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41712", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for a request to download a file (ChromeSetup.bat) from an external network, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique where adversaries transfer tools or files into a compromised environment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42255: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42255",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1021",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use Valid Accounts to log into a service that accepts remote connections, such as telnet, SSH, and VNC\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to establish a Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) connection from an external network to an internal system, which aligns with the \\\'Remote Services\\\' technique where adversaries leverage remote services to gain access to systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42255", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1133",\\n    "Technique name": "External Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may leverage external-facing remote services to initially access and/or persist within a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically targets connections from an external network ($EXTERNAL_NET) to an internal system ($HOME_NET) on port 3389, which is the default port for RDP. column5: {895: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "895",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting an attempt to access a \\\'/redirect\\\' path on a public-facing web server, which could potentially be an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the web application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "895", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "By attempting to access the \\\'/redirect\\\' path, the activity detected by the Snort rule could be an attempt to discover and enumerate running services on the web server, which is a step in identifying potential vulnerabilities to exploit."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38566: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38566",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Sweeper) attempting to download a malicious binary file using the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS), which is commonly abused by adversaries to execute code and perform tasks in the background."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38566", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for an attempt to download a binary file (with a .bin extension) from an external network, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique where adversaries transfer malicious tools or files into the compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57067: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57067",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to write a file to the HP Web JetAdmin server using the \\\'/plugins/framework/script/tree.xms\\\' URI, which could be an abuse of a legitimate server component for malicious purposes, such as establishing persistence or executing code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57067", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1647",\\n    "Technique name": "Plist File Modification",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may modify property list files (plist files) to enable other malicious activity, while also potentially evading and bypassing system defenses\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule does not explicitly mention modifying plist files, the attempt to write a file to the server could potentially be used to modify configuration files or other system files, which could enable further malicious activity or evasion of defenses."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50464: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1135",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Share Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may look for folders and drives shared on remote systems as a means of identifying sources of information to gather as a precursor for Collection and to identify potential systems of interest for Lateral Movement\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to enumerate network shares using the NetServer service on port 445, which is commonly used for Network Share Discovery by adversaries to identify potential targets for lateral movement or data collection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1018",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote System Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of other systems by IP address, hostname, or other logical identifier on a network that may be used for Lateral Movement from the current system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting an attempt to enumerate systems on the network using the NetServer service, which could be part of Remote System Discovery to identify potential targets for lateral movement."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57738: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57738",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a request to the Active Directory Federation Services (ADFS) policy store transfer service, which could potentially be used by an adversary to perform an Adversary-in-the-Middle attack by intercepting and manipulating the policy store data during transfer."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {30524: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30524",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1595",\\n    "Technique name": "Active Scanning",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may execute active reconnaissance scans to gather information that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to exploit the OpenSSL TLSv1.1 heartbeat read overrun vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160), which is a form of active scanning or reconnaissance activity used by adversaries to identify vulnerable systems before launching further attacks."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30524", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for exploitation attempts against the OpenSSL TLSv1.1 implementation, which is a public-facing application used for secure communication over the internet. column5: {28351: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28351",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1047",\\n    "Technique name": "Windows Management Instrumentation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to execute malicious commands and payloads\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to access the Microsoft Windows WMI administrator tools object viewer ActiveX control, which could be used by an adversary to execute malicious commands and payloads via WMI."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28351", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the detected activity may be related to an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in a client application (ActiveX control) to execute code on the target system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1292: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1292",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect potential directory listing attempts, which aligns with the File and Directory Discovery technique where adversaries enumerate files and directories to gather information."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1292", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1135",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Share Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may look for folders and drives shared on remote systems as a means of identifying sources of information to gather as a precursor for Collection and to identify potential systems of interest for Lateral Movement\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule mentions \\\'Volume Serial Number\\\', which could indicate an attempt to discover network shares, aligning with the Network Share Discovery technique used by adversaries to identify potential sources of information."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {22034: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n    {\\n        "sid": "22034",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n        "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n        "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from an infected system to an external server, which is a common technique used by malware to communicate with its command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n    },\\n    {\\n        "sid": "22034",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n        "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n        "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions that it is detecting a variant of the Flashback malware, which is known to masquerade as legitimate software updates to evade detection."\\n    }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1122: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1122",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1087",\\n    "Technique name": "Account Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of valid accounts, usernames, or email addresses on a system or within a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to access the /etc/passwd file, which contains user account information on Unix-based systems. column5: {1434: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1434",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .bash_history file, which contains a record of commands executed in the Bash shell. column5: {21442: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21442",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1001",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect obfuscated command and control traffic, specifically when the URI request is base64 encoded, which is a common obfuscation technique used by malware to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21442", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1132",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Encoding",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may encode data to make the content of command and control traffic more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule explicitly checks for base64 encoded data in the URI request, which is a form of data encoding used by malware to obfuscate command and control traffic and evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {27968: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27968",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects activity related to the Chopper web shell, which is a malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and execute commands on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27968", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for incoming HTTP traffic from external sources, which could indicate an attempt to exploit a public-facing web application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {27966: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27966",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects a connection from an external network to an internal web server, potentially indicating an attempt to exploit a public-facing application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27966", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1133",\\n    "Technique name": "External Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may leverage external-facing remote services to initially access and/or persist within a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a specific web shell (Chopper) being used, which is a type of remote access tool that can be leveraged by adversaries to maintain access to a compromised system via external remote services."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37257: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37257",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer by loading the mapi32x.dll library, which could allow an adversary to execute code on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37257", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "By exploiting a vulnerability in Internet Explorer, an adversary could potentially bypass security defenses and execute malicious code on the client system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56594: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56594",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malware download attempt, which suggests that an adversary is attempting to transfer a malicious tool or file (GORAT malware) from an external system to the compromised environment, aligning with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56594", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule indicates that the adversary is attempting to download and potentially install the GORAT malware, which could provide additional capabilities for further malicious activities, corresponding to the Stage Capabilities technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59502: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59502",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability in the Microsoft Windows Server 2003 Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) service, which is a remote service. This aligns with the technique \\\'Exploitation of Remote Services\\\' where adversaries exploit vulnerabilities in remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59502", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1021",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use Valid Accounts to log into a service that accepts remote connections, such as telnet, SSH, and VNC\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically targeting the Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) service, which is a remote service used for remote access and administration. This technique is relevant as adversaries may leverage valid accounts to log into remote services like RDP for malicious purposes."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {23780: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23780",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a compromised system to an external network, which could be an indication of command and control communication using the application layer protocol HTTP.
